The US Supreme Court is deliberating on the legality of executing criminals under 18, with international pressure mounting.
Advocates argue against juvenile executions, citing evolving standards of decency.
The case of Christopher Simmons, sentenced to death at 17, has sparked debate on whether minors can fully comprehend their actions.
Justices are divided on whether such executions serve justice or are relics of the past.
The court is also addressing issues like federal sentencing guidelines and racial segregation in prisons.
The outcome will shape the future of capital punishment for young offenders, reflecting changing societal norms.
